anvil.api.ServerOutputLine

Class ServerOutputLine

  • java.lang.Object
    • anvil.api.ServerOutputLine.ServerOutputLine

  • public class ServerOutputLine
extends java.lang.Object
    Represents a ServerOutputLine from the Minecraft server in a Runner. These are the lines that the server return to the user by running the server. They can be retrieved with the Runner.getNextOutputLine() method.

    Minecraft servers give fairly useful information in their output lines. The only annoying thing is that are so many possibilities for types of output lines! To deal with this issue, you can create your own types by implementing the ServerOutputLineType interface. Or you can use one of the Defaults.

    Version:
    1.0
    Author:
    Garrett Stonis
    See Also:
    ServerOutputLineType, Defaults, Runner

        Constructs a ServerOutputLine object with a ServerOutputLineType and the contents of the line.

        While a ServerOutputLine object can be made anywhere, only Anvil's generated output lines will be passed to each PlugIn.interpretServerOutputLine(String, ServerOutputLine) method.

        Parameters:
        entire_line - String object containing every part of the ServerOutputLine. Literally the entire line that the server returns.

        Throws:

      • getType

        public ServerOutputLineType getType()
        Gets the type of the ServerOutputLine.

        The type is what distinguishes each output line from each other one. It identifies where the output line's useful information is. Based on addKnownType(Class), each ServerOutputLineType must be an enumeration, forcing simple classification. If the type is null, there was no known ServerOutputLineType enumeration that properly classified the line, making it generic and locking most of its information.

        Returns:
        The ServerOutputLineType representing the type of the ServerOutputLine. Null if generic.
        See Also:
        ServerOutputLineType

      • addKnownType

        public static <T extends java.lang.Enum<?> & ServerOutputLineType> void addKnownType(java.lang.Class<T> newType)
        Adds a new instance of a ServerOutputLineType to Anvil. Cannot be undone.

        All new ServerOutputLineTypes must extend the Enum class (being an enum counts), and implement the ServerOutputLineType interface to be added.

        All of the known types will be checked to see if any of them pertain to the contents given. The Defaults are checked last, but then the load order is as random as the PlugIns being loaded. To do this properly, all additions should be made in the PlugIn.onLoad() method.

        Some notes on creating unobtrusive ServerOutputLineTypes:

        • Make the acceptedFormats as specific as possible, as not to take over unintentional lines.
        • Take full advantage of regex patterns, don't make a bunch of enumerations where they aren't needed.
        • List any added types for other developers/users. Anvil will use the first match it comes across every time. Can cause confusion if developers/users were expecting to use 1 specific type.
        • Don't try to overwrite other types, apart from the Defaults. Even then, only overwrite them if you need functionality that the Defaults don't provide in their current state.
        • Don't do anything too fancy in the ServerOutputLineType method overrides, everything complicated is handled by ServerOutputLine anyways.
        Type Parameters:
        T - Any class that extends Enum (being an enum counts) and implements the ServerOutputLineType interface.
        Parameters:
        newType - The class of the new ServerOutputLineType to add to the known list.
